# Fluff Date: 2026-02-20 17:30:00
overview:<p>The Toyama is a seventy-five-ton heavy BattleMech designed and built for the Word of Blake following their exodus to Gibson in the Free Worlds League. Unlike many Word of Blake designs produced in-house, the Toyama was the work of an outsider, a military technology consultant with the Free Worlds League's Heliopolis design labs. As part of an arrangement with Captain-General Thomas Marik, the design was passed to the Word of Blake, who put it into production in early 3057 at the Gibson Federated BattleMechs facilities. Named for Conrad Toyama, the successor to Jerome Blake as Primus of ComStar and the acknowledged founder of the Blakist religion, the design was intended as a multi-purpose 'Mech capable of operating independently of supply lines for extended periods. The Toyama became one of the most recognizable Word of Blake BattleMechs, serving as a mainstay of the Blakist Militia throughout the Jihad.</p>

capabilities:<p>Designed for versatility and endurance, the Toyama carries an impressive mix of weapons systems covering all engagement ranges. A pair of Diverse Optics Sunbeam extended-range large lasers mounted in the right arm provide devastating long-range firepower, while an Imperator Code Red LB 10-X autocannon in the left arm offers flexibility through both standard and cluster munitions. A Doombud LRM-20 launcher in the torso adds indirect fire capability, with two full tons of ammunition allowing the pilot to carry a mix of warhead types tailored to the mission at hand. Three Magna Mark II medium lasers clustered in the torso provide additional close-range firepower, though their effective range is limited.</p><p>The Toyama is built on a lightweight Endo Steel chassis powered by a Vlar 300 XL engine, giving it a top speed of sixty-five kilometers per hour, adequate for keeping pace with most heavy 'Mech formations. Twelve tons of Durallex Heavy armor provide substantial protection for its weight class. A Guardian ECM suite mounted in the right torso disrupts enemy electronic warfare systems, though the original design's planned anti-missile system was ultimately sacrificed to accommodate the larger LRM launcher.</p>

deployment:<p>The original Toyama was deployed exclusively with the Word of Blake Militia from its introduction in 3057. The design proved effective during Operation Odysseus and subsequently became one of the most common heavy 'Mechs in Blakist formations. Its combination of long-range energy weapons, an autocannon with flexible ammunition options, missile bombardment capability, and electronic warfare protection made it well-suited to the independent operations that Word of Blake units frequently conducted. The Guardian ECM suite proved particularly valuable in disrupting enemy targeting systems during the opening phases of the Jihad.</p>

history:<p>The Toyama first saw combat with the Word of Blake Militia during the late 3050s. Plans to deploy several Toyamas to the Atrean Dragoons were postponed when the Word of Blake launched Operation Odysseus in 3058, during which Blakist Militia troops masquerading as the mercenary 21st Centauri Lancers infiltrated and sabotaged ComStar's defenses on Terra. At least four Toyamas were used during that operation, marking the design's baptism of fire.</p><p>Following the seizure of Terra, the Toyama became increasingly common among Blakist forces. Gibson Federated BattleMechs, a division of Free Worlds Defense Industries, ramped up production at their facilities on Gibson throughout the Civil War era. By the time of the Jihad, the Word of Blake had established a second production line at the Lantren Corporation facility on Bryant, which intelligence analysts had long suspected based on the volume of new Toyamas appearing in combat zones far exceeding projected output from Gibson alone.</p><p>During the Jihad, both factories operated at full capacity producing the original TYM-1A along with newly developed variants incorporating advanced technologies. The Gibson facility produced all three known variants, while the Bryant line focused on the TYM-1A and the advanced TYM-1C. Word of Blake engineers on Gibson continued refining the design throughout the conflict, producing machines that combined increased durability with devastating firepower.</p><p>The destruction wrought during the Jihad brought Toyama production to a permanent halt. Both the Gibson and Bryant facilities ceased operations during or shortly after the conflict, and no faction has resumed manufacturing of the design. Surviving Toyamas remain in service with various successor states and mercenary commands that captured them during the Jihad, but the 'Mech's strong association with the Word of Blake has given it a lasting stigma that has discouraged any attempts to revive production.</p>

